, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bromwich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from West Bromwich (Staffs) or Castle and Little Bromwich (Warwicks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brommage","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]},{"name":"Brumage","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bromage  ."]},{"name":"Bromage","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): habitational name from West Bromwich in Staffordshire, or Castle and Little Bromwich in Warwickshire, named in Old English with <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ (the shrub) + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. Compare   Brumage  ."]},{"name":"Brimage","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Brumage  . This name is comparatively rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bromige","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Alan de Bromwich II was born in 1180, in Bromsgrove, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Alan de Bromwich I and Madam Bromwich. He married Madam Bromwich about 1215, in Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1250, in England, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1180–about 1250":"1180–umbes 1250","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1225–1287":"1225–1287","–Male":"Surnud","1150–1210":"1150–1210","–Female":"Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1210":"1210","1287":"1287","about 1179":"umbes 1179","about 1210":"umbes 1210","Pedmore, Bromsgrove, Warwickshire, England":"Bromsgrove, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","England":"England","Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Bromwich, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1180–about 1250":"1180–noin 1250","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1225–1287":"1225–1287","–Male":"Kuollut","1150–1210":"1150–1210","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","about 1215":"noin 1215